modules.description: This module maps performance measurement units to string representations, providing functions to add labeled units, retrieve them by label, and format them as Notty images for display. It works with strings, hashtables, and Bechamel measurement witnesses. It is used to annotate and visualize benchmarking metrics in terminal interfaces using the Notty library.

This module defines and manages sorting orders (increasing or decreasing) for benchmarking measurements. It provides functions to compare values based on a given order, and maps string labels to order types. It is used to control and apply consistent sorting logic when displaying or analyzing performance metrics.

This module renders performance analysis data into terminal images using Notty. It provides functions to generate images from regression results, compare best and worst cases, and display headers and fields for specific predictors. It works with rectangles, hashtables of statistical data, and OLS regression results, primarily for visualizing benchmarking metrics in a terminal.

This module renders benchmarking results and statistical data as terminal images using Notty. It provides functions to visualize headers, OLS regression fields, and sorted OLS results, supporting customizable display dimensions and sorting. It is used to generate terminal-based reports from performance analysis data, particularly for comparing benchmark outcomes across different configurations or runs.

This module enables the creation of terminal-based visualizations and UI layouts using ASCII graphics, while offering utilities for hash table manipulation and performance data rendering. It centers around `Notty.image` for visualizing geometric shapes and statistical data, with operations for key-value extraction from hashtables and layout composition. The child modules enhance this functionality by mapping performance units to visual elements, defining sorting logic for benchmark data, and rendering analysis results into terminal images. Examples include building interactive benchmark reports, visualizing OLS regression outcomes, and organizing statistical data in sortable, labeled UI components.
